AutoOPE: Automated Off-Policy Estimator Selection

Nicolò Felicioni
Politecnico di Milano
nicolo.felicioni@polimi.it
&Michael Benigni
Politecnico di Milano
michael.benigni@polimi.it
Maurizio Ferrari Dacrema
Politecnico di Milano
maurizio.ferrari@polimi.it
Abstract

The Off-Policy Evaluation (OPE) problem consists of evaluating the performance of counterfactual policies with data collected by another one. This problem is of utmost importance for various application domains, e.g., recommendation systems, medical treatments, and many others. To solve the OPE problem, we resort to estimators, which aim to estimate in the most accurate way possible the performance that the counterfactual policies would have had if they were deployed in place of the logging policy. In the literature, several estimators have been developed, all with different characteristics and theoretical guarantees. Therefore, there is no dominant estimator, and each estimator may be the best one for different OPE problems, depending on the characteristics of the dataset at hand. While the selection of the estimator is a crucial choice for an accurate OPE, this problem has been widely overlooked in the literature. We propose an automated data-driven OPE estimator selection method based on machine learning. In particular, the core idea we propose in this paper is to create several synthetic OPE tasks and use a machine learning model trained to predict the best estimator for those synthetic tasks. We empirically show how our method is able to generalize to unseen tasks and make a better estimator selection compared to a baseline method on several real-world datasets, with a computational cost significantly lower than the one of the baseline.

1 Introduction

In numerous real-world scenarios, decision-making systems are required to interact with dynamic environments, making choices aimed at optimizing specific objectives. These systems are prevalent in domains such as recommender systems [10, 30, 7], information retrieval [22], ad-placement systems [4], or medical treatments [9]. Such decision-making problems can be viewed through the lens of the Contextual Bandit paradigm [43, 19]. For instance, let us consider the recommendation system domain: the recommender (agent) repeatedly observes user profiles (contexts), and aims to recommend items (actions) to users based on the given context to maximize some notion of reward.

A critical challenge arises in evaluating the performance of new policies without deploying them in the real world. This is especially pertinent in scenarios where deploying a suboptimal policy can have significant negative consequences, such as lost revenue in ad placement or user dissatisfaction in recommender systems. Off-Policy Evaluation (OPE) seeks to address this challenge by evaluating the performance of counterfactual policies using data collected from a different, previously deployed policy, often termed the logging policy. The ability to make informed decisions about policy modifications without necessitating real-world deployment is not only cost-effective but also reduces the potential risks associated with untested policies.

However, the effectiveness of OPE largely hinges on the accuracy of the estimator used to predict the performance of the evaluation policies. There is a wide variety of estimators that have been proposed in the literature, each with distinct characteristics and mathematical properties [41]. As an example, a well-known estimator, called Inverse Propensity Scoring (IPS) [29, 34], mitigates the estimation bias by adjusting observed rewards based on the inverse probability assigned by the logging policy to the logged action. In this way, actions that have a low probability under the logging policy receive higher weighting to compensate for their infrequent occurrence in the dataset, and vice versa for actions more likely under the logging policy. Despite IPS’s prominence, numerous other estimators exist, each with unique trade-offs between bias and variance. Given the heterogeneity of real-world datasets and the myriad of scenarios in which OPE is applied, no single estimator is universally optimal. Further details on related work are reported in Appendix A. An estimator may be the best under certain circumstances but perform poorly under others. This variety of estimators, while offering flexibility, also introduces the challenge of Estimator Selection, which is a crucial problem in OPE and has been mostly overlooked in the existing literature. Basically, the Estimator Selection problem consists of the following: we are given an Off-Policy Evaluation task and we have to select the best estimator for the task we have at hand.

In this paper, we address the Estimator Selection problem using an automated data-driven approach. Our main idea consists of exploiting synthetic data. We generate several different synthetic OPE tasks by varying the characteristics of each one. Various types of estimators are applied to these tasks, and their estimates are compared against the ground-truth value of each evaluation policy, which is known due to the synthetic nature of the data. These synthetic OPE tasks are used to train a machine learning model designed to predict estimator’s Mean Squared Errors for the given OPE task. This model can select the estimator with the lowest predicted error, effectively addressing the OPE Estimator Selection challenge. We call our Estimator Selection method Automated Off-Policy Estimator Selection (AutoOPE). The problem of Estimator Selection has been widely overlooked in the literature, and, to the best of our knowledge, only a very recent paper [40] proposed a method for Estimator Selection, named Policy-Adaptive Estimator Selection via Importance Fitting (PAS-IF), which is substantially different from our proposal.

In this paper, we propose a novel data-driven approach called Automated Off-Policy Estimator Selection (AutoOPE) to address the Estimator Selection problem in Off-Policy Evaluation. Our key contributions are:

  • •

    We train a machine learning model to predict the performance of estimators on a large number of synthetic OPE tasks with varying characteristics. We share the code for our experiments for researchers and practitioners in the field111We anonymously share the code to reproduce our experiments: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/auto-ope-28F3/.

  • •

    To the best of our knowledge, this is the first work to address the estimator selection problem in OPE using a data-driven approach leveraging only synthetic data, and it is one of the few techniques proposed for Estimator Selection in OPE in general, despite the importance of the problem.

  • •

    We conduct extensive experiments on several datasets that empirically demonstrate the effectiveness of our proposed AutoOPE method in selecting high-performing estimators tailored to the given OPE task, performing better than the baseline with a much reduced computational cost. This represents an important contribution towards automated and adaptive Off-Policy Evaluation.

2.3 Estimator Selection for OPE

The effectiveness of OPE crucially depends on how accurate is the estimator in estimating the policy value of the evaluation policy, usually in terms of how low is its M⁢S⁢E⁢(V^⁢(πe))𝑀𝑆𝐸^𝑉subscript𝜋𝑒MSE(\hat{V}(\pi_{e}))italic_M italic_S italic_E ( over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG ( italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ). For this reason, and since many OPE estimators have been proposed in the literature, selecting the best estimator for a given OPE task, i.e., Estimator Selection, is particularly important. Given a finite set 𝒱𝒱\mathcal{V}caligraphic_V of different OPE estimators, the Estimator Selection problem consists in finding the best estimator among them.

Since in OPE we do not have any data collected under the evaluation policy, we cannot compute the ground-truth evaluation policy value V⁢(πe)𝑉subscript𝜋𝑒V(\pi_{e})italic_V ( italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) and therefore the ground-truth MSE of the estimator. A common approach is to approximate it with an estimate, i.e., M⁢S⁢E^⁢(V^⁢(πe))^𝑀𝑆𝐸^𝑉subscript𝜋𝑒\widehat{MSE}(\hat{V}(\pi_{e}))over^ start_ARG italic_M italic_S italic_E end_ARG ( over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG ( italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ), and to select the estimator that has the lowest approximate MSE.

3 Automated Off-Policy Estimator Selection

In this section, we present a novel approach for solving the Estimator Selection problem, called Automated Off-Policy Estimator Selection (AutoOPE).

3.2 Practical Implementation

However, this approach is feasible if we have access to several OPE tasks, a feature extraction function, and the ground-truth MSE. For this reason, our approach extensively rely on synthetic data. Specifically:

Dataset

We generate a meta-dataset ℳ≔{𝒯ope(1),𝒯ope(2),…}≔ℳsuperscriptsubscript𝒯ope1superscriptsubscript𝒯ope2…\mathcal{M}\coloneqq\{\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^{(1)},\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^% {(2)},\dots\}caligraphic_M ≔ { caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( 1 ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( 2 ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , … } composed of several different synthetic OPE tasks. In this way, we have access to the ground-truth MSE. Also, since the objective is to obtain a model that is able to generalize in a zero-shot way, we want to train our model with a large number of OPE tasks. This would be unfeasible using real-world OPE data, which is scarce. We indeed generate 250,000 synthetic OPE tasks. Furthermore, to favor generalization of our model, we create OPE tasks with different numerical characteristics. For more details on the synthetic data generation, we refer to Appendix C.

Features

Regarding the features g𝑔gitalic_g, while theoretical results have proven a relation, for instance, with the exponentiated Rényi divergence, we want to take into account a wide selection of possible features. Hence, we designed a total of 43 features. In particular, we categorize the features into three groups: (i) Policies-independent features, that describe structural properties of the CB scenario and are unrelated from the specific πb,πesubscript𝜋𝑏subscript𝜋𝑒\pi_{b},\ \pi_{e}italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, e.g., the number of rounds, the reward variance, the number of actions. (ii) Policies-dependent features, such as the dissimilarity between the two policies πb,πesubscript𝜋𝑏subscript𝜋𝑒\pi_{b},\ \pi_{e}italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, measured with different statistical distances and divergences. (iii) OPE estimator features, that refer to specific properties of the OPE estimator used in that task, e.g., if the estimator is self-normalized, or uses importance sampling. See Appendix E for their full description.

Estimators

The set 𝒱𝒱\mathcal{V}caligraphic_V of candidate estimators include several model-free, model-based and hybrid estimators, as done in [40]. All the estimators used are described in Appendix B.

Model

As a supervised model f^^𝑓\hat{f}over^ start_ARG italic_f end_ARG, we use a Random Forest regressor [5] because of its high-quality predictions on tabular data and its speed, both in training and inference. For more details on training and optimization, we refer to Appendix D.

We recap the AutoOPE method in Algorithms 1 (training of the model) and 2 (zero-shot estimator selection).

The AutoOPE approach has several advantages. First of all, it is data-driven: AutoOPE tries to learn the shared patterns in several different synthetic OPE tasks with the objective to generalize to new unseen tasks. For this, we use a Random Forest, which is a powerful and fast model for tabular data. Furthermore, it is theory-inspired: it stems from theoretical findings to create a data-driven model that takes in input features such as divergences which are proven to be related to the estimator’s error, but also features that have no theoretical guarantee at the moment. Thanks to this, we can also provide insights that can shed light on future theoretical findings by analyzing the features that had a significant impact on the model’s performance. Finally, it is zero-shot. This means that a practitioner can avoid training for each new estimator selection task, leading to a much faster computational time.

A possible downside of our approach is that we trained AutoOPE on large meta-dataset ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M that is synthetic and created a priori, which may not lead to generalization to particular real-world OPE tasks. However, in Section 4, we show that AutoOPE generalizes well to unseen real-world OPE tasks with an extensive experimental evaluation on a large number of real-world OPE tasks.

4 Experiments

In this section, we describe the experimental analysis of our proposed AutoOPE and show it is competitive with the PAS-IF baseline on several real-world tasks, as well as exhibiting a lower computational cost.

4.1 Experimental Settings

PAS-IF Baseline

Our proposed method is compared to the PAS-IF baseline, which has specific hyperparameters. One important drawback of PAS-IF is the high computational cost, see Section 4.3, which makes hyperparameter tuning impractical.333We estimate that applying the same Bayesian Search used for AutoOPE would require at least a month of high-end GPU usage. For this reason we rely on the ad-hoc strategy presented in [40] which tunes the regularization parameter λ𝜆\lambdaitalic_λ for each new OPE task via grid search.

AutoOPE

We train the Random Forest model of AutoOPE on the synthetic meta-dataset ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M and we optimize its hyperparameters with a Bayesian search. For more details, we refer to Appendix D. In this Section, we only use the trained Random Forest in inference, in a zero-shot way (see Algorithm 2) on new unseen tasks.

Evaluation Metrics for OPE Selection

To evaluate AutoOPE and PAS-IF on the Estimator Selection task we use two metrics: Relative Regret and Spearman’s Rank Correlation Coefficient, as in [40], leveraging the fact that in all experiments we have access to the ground-truth MSE of each estimator. Further details are in Appendix H.

Spearman’s Rank Correlation Coefficient [33] measures the similarity between two rankings, one based on the MSE predicted by the Estimator Selection method and the other based on the ground-truth MSE.

4.2 Results

Here we present the results we obtained on several public real-world datasets.

4.2.1 Open Bandit Dataset (OBD)

In this real-world experiment, we use the Open Bandit Dataset (OBD) [31], a publicly available dataset originated from a large-scale fashion e-commerce platform. The dataset encompasses three campaigns: ‘ALL’, ‘MEN’, and ‘WOMEN’. In each campaign, the deployed policy is randomly chosen at each round, selecting either the Uniform Random policy or the Bernoulli Thompson Sampling policy.

CB Data

We focus on the ‘ALL’ campaign, and opt to employ the bandit feedback collected under the Uniform Random policy as logging data, while the data collected under the Bernoulli Thompson Sampling policy serves as evaluation data. In order to compute confidence intervals, we perform stratified bootstrap sampling 20 times. Each subsample consists of around 35,000 rounds and constitutes a new OPE task.

Results

The outcomes of this experiment are shown in Table 1. Our AutoOPE method exhibits a Relative Regret almost 6 times lower compared to PAS-IF, and the Spearman’s Rank Correlation Coefficient is much better than PAS-IF. AutoOPE confirms its stability in its predictions, exhibiting low variance, while PAS-IF has a large variance especially on Relative Regret. This experiment confirms that AutoOPE, while being trained on synthetic data, is able to generalize on data coming from real distributions.

Results

The results are shown in Figure 1. AutoOPE consistently outperforms PAS-IF, demonstrating lower Relative Regret and better Spearman’s Rank Correlation Coefficient in almost all the 40 different experimental configurations. Indeed, AutoOPE outperforms PAS-IF 36 out of 40 configurations in terms of Spearman’s Coefficient, and 37 out of 40 configurations in terms of Relative Regret, even if AutoOPE performs estimator selection in a zero-shot way. Notably, when AutoOPE outperforms PAS-IF, it does it by a large margin. Also, AutoOPE exhibits lower variance in particular for the Spearman’s coefficient, while PAS-IF exhibits very high variance. This comprehensive empirical evaluation and its results are consistent with the OBD experiments and confirm that AutoOPE is able to generalize to unseen OPE tasks with a different distribution compared to the one used for its training, in a zero-shot fashion.

4.3 Computational Time Comparison

One important advantage of our AutoOPE method is that, after the pre-training phase, it is ready-to-use for inference, potentially on many different datasets and evaluation policies. On the other hand, the baseline method PAS-IF must be trained from scratch and perform hyperparameter optimization for every new evaluation policy and dataset. Due to this, the time required to perform the Estimator Selection task is very different. Figure 3 reports a comparison of the time required to perform the Estimator Selection task. As expected, AutoOPE is in the order of 10 times faster compared to PAS-IF, even though PAS-IF performs estimator selection on a GPU, while AutoOPE does it on a CPU. Further details are reported in Appendix G.

4.4 Additional Experiments

Finally, we conducted other additional experiments on more datasets, various ablation studies, as well as an analysis of the most important features of the AutoOPE model.

Feature Importance

A useful benefit of using Random Forest models is that we can compute the feature importance. For this analysis we use the Mean Decrease in Impurity (MDI), meaning that features with higher importance scores are more influential in the model decision-making process. Figure 3 shows a selection of features for the Random Forest model. The full plot is in Figure 4 of Appendix E. To assess the importance of each feature group, let us focus on the 15 most and least important features in the full plot of Figure 4 in Appendix E. The 11 policy-independent features appear to be of limited importance and correspond to 4 of the 15 least important features. Only 1 policy-dependent feature belongs to the first 15 most important features, which is the 4th moment of the logged rewards and is the second most important feature. Policy-dependent features, which are 24, are generally useful for the model, with 10 among the 15 most important features and 6 out of 24 among the 15 least important. The KL divergence is the most important feature, which suggests further theoretical study may be warranted. The 8 OPE estimator features are similarly spread, with 4 among the most important features and 5 among the least important ones. In particular, among the most important OPE estimator features there are features that characterize the type of estimator (if it uses a reward model or importance sampling or both).

The insights gained from this feature importance analysis is an important contribution. In particular, it can shed light on future theoretical findings, lead by analyzing the features that had a significant impact on the model’s performance.

Additional Experiments and Ablation studies

We conducted additional experiments on estimator selection on synthetic datasets and on the CIFAR dataset [18]. Also, we conducted different ablation studies, investigating the impact of scaling the size of the meta-dataset, the diversity of the meta-dataset, and the features used. We describe all these additional experiments in Appendix F.

5 Conclusions

In this paper, we focused on the Estimator Selection problem in Off-Policy Evaluation. We showed that, despite its significance, it is an overlooked problem in the literature. We proposed AutoOPE, a novel data-driven approach for Estimator Selection, which leverages synthetic OPE tasks in order to learn to generalize the estimator selection capabilities to unseen real-world OPE tasks. Through several experiments, we empirically showed how our method is able to consistently make a better estimator selection when compared to the baseline method on several real-world datasets, outperforming the baseline method by a large margin with a significantly lower computational cost.

For future work, a natural direction to follow would be to try different machine learning models for AutoOPE, in particular for scenarios where one may want further guarantees on the Estimator Selection process. Furthermore, one could try to theoretically analyze the relationship between the features of the AutoOPE meta-dataset and the performance of the various estimators, which was unveiled by the feature importance of the random forest model. Finally, our approach focused on the estimator selection problem in the contextual bandit domain. Our method could be used as a stepping stone towards improving OPE estimator selection in the more general Reinforcement Learning scenario.

Appendix A Related Work

In the realm of Contextual Bandit Off-Policy Evaluation, there exists a rich and diverse landscape of published research aimed at assessing the performance of policies without actually deploying them, avoiding the hazard of selecting action under not valuable or deleterious policies which, depending on the scenario, could be costly and dangerous [10, 21, 30, 17]. Indeed, this area of study has brought contributions to various application domains, including recommender systems [22], advertising [4], and precision medicine [23], reflecting its flexibility in modeling different situations. In this context, AutoOPE emerges as a novel approach, offering a unique solution based on a black-box model that leverages synthetic data and meta-learning to tackle the Estimator Selection problem.

To appreciate the significance of AutoOPE, it is essential to understand the broader context of Contextual Bandit OPE research.

Several pioneering works have laid the foundation for evaluating counterfactual policies in the context of Contextual Bandit. Notable contributions include studies that have introduced fundamental approaches such as the Direct Method (DM) [3], Inverse Propensity Scoring (IPS) [29, 34], and Doubly Robust (DR) [38, 12, 6], which serve as the cornerstone for OPE research, since they define the three main classes of OPE estimators: model-based, model-free and hybrid.

Direct Method (DM) is rooted in machine learning, employing algorithms to estimate policy performance by regressing rewards. Its effectiveness depends on the precision of the reward estimation produced by the learning algorithm. For this reason, its performance may decrease specially in complex environments like industrial recommender systems. DM is susceptible to bias when the model does not produce accurate reward estimations, caused by the inability to correct the distribution shift between the observed data and the counterfactual policy. It is a purely model-based estimator.

Inverse Propensity Scoring (IPS) instead is purely model-free. IPS is unbiased on expectation, thanks to the employment of the notion of importance sampling by statistics, but exhibits high variance, that increases when logging and evaluation policies are significantly different.

Doubly Robust (DR) represents a blend of DM and IPS characteristics, since it is unbiased and generally presents a lower variance compared to IPS. However, its performance still depends on the specific task so it is not necessarily the best option.

A multitude of OPE estimators, has been designed over time as extensions or combinations of DM, IPS and DR [37, 14, 35, 26, 38, 44]. These efforts collectively contribute to advance OPE methodologies.

However, many estimators incorporate hyperparameters to balance the bias-variance trade-off given the Contextual Bandit environment such as [35, 26, 38, 12, 6, 44]. As reported by [32, 31] the hyperparameter tuning strongly affects the prediction quality. To address the issue of hyperparameter optimization [36] and [39] proposed SLOPE and its improved version SLOPE++, based on Lepski’s principle [20], offering improved results compared to naïve tuning procedures. Lepski’s principle allows to define an upper-bound for the Mean Squared Error without delving into the bias estimation, that is the main reason why the task of MSE estimation is challenging. SLOPE dominates all the other methods designed for hyperparameter tuning, being the state of the art technique for this task. Other existing methods like MAGIC [38], or other built-in methods of proposed estimators [35, 44] have tackled hyperparameter selection using MSE estimators, but they offer weaker guarantees compared to SLOPE.

The Estimator Selection problem has emerged as a relatively unexplored but pivotal aspect of OPE research. Empirical studies by [42] and [32] have shown the fundamental role of Estimator Selection on OPE accuracy, highlighting its importance in practical applications.

In this context, the recent PAS-IF (Policy-Adaptive Estimator Selection via Importance Fitting) method [40] emerges as the only baseline for Estimator Selection. PAS-IF uses a neural network to learn a subsampling rule that is used to generate two pseudo-datasets starting from the available logging data. The subsampling rule is learned by optimizing an importance fitting loss that depends on the specific logging and evaluation policies one wishes to evaluate. Once the two pseudo datasets have been generated, PAS-IF allows to estimate the candidate estimators’ Mean Squared Error based on the empirical average of rewards in these pseudo datasets.

Our proposed AutoOPE method, on the other hand, competes with PAS-IF in performance by introducing a novel data-driven approach that leverages meta-learning with synthetic data and a black-box model. AutoOPE offers a versatile approach, allowing the comparison of different estimator classes and the selection of the most accurate one. This innovative approach empirically promises to significantly enhance the accuracy of OPE, reducing an important gap in the Contextual Bandit Off-Policy Evaluation field.

Appendix C Meta-Dataset

C.1 Characteristics

As stated in Section 3, AutoOPE method is based on a zero-shot meta-learning approach framed as a supervised learning problem. In particular, the goal of this supervised learning problem is to predict, given an estimator V^msubscript^𝑉𝑚\hat{V}_{m}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and an OPE task 𝒯ope(j)superscriptsubscript𝒯ope𝑗\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^{(j)}caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as input, the M⁢S⁢E𝑀𝑆𝐸MSEitalic_M italic_S italic_E of V^msubscript^𝑉𝑚\hat{V}_{m}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT when applied to 𝒯ope(j)superscriptsubscript𝒯ope𝑗\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^{(j)}caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT.

Hence, to train a Random Forest regressor to predict this MSE, we need a finite set of possible estimators 𝒱𝒱\mathcal{V}caligraphic_V such that V^m∈𝒱subscript^𝑉𝑚𝒱\hat{V}_{m}\in\mathcal{V}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ∈ caligraphic_V defined a-priori, and a large set of OPE tasks ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M. The set ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M is a collection of synthetically generated OPE tasks, obtained from a data generator function G𝐺Gitalic_G, which we describe in further detail in Section C.2.

The training dataset for the Random Forest is obtained extracting suitable input features from the estimator V^msubscript^𝑉𝑚\hat{V}_{m}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and an OPE task 𝒯ope(j)superscriptsubscript𝒯ope𝑗\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^{(j)}caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, that the Random Forest can work with. This is done using a feature extraction function g𝑔gitalic_g. Then, the target is the ground-truth M⁢S⁢E𝑀𝑆𝐸MSEitalic_M italic_S italic_E of V^msubscript^𝑉𝑚\hat{V}_{m}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT when applied to 𝒯ope(j)superscriptsubscript𝒯ope𝑗\mathcal{T}_{\text{ope}}^{(j)}caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT ope end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. The training dataset can be expressed as: {g⁢(𝒱×ℳ),M⁢S⁢E⁢(𝒱×ℳ)}𝑔𝒱ℳ𝑀𝑆𝐸𝒱ℳ\{g(\mathcal{V}\times\mathcal{M}),\ MSE(\mathcal{V}\times\mathcal{M})\}{ italic_g ( caligraphic_V × caligraphic_M ) , italic_M italic_S italic_E ( caligraphic_V × caligraphic_M ) }

The meta-learning dataset ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M contains 250,000250000250,000250 , 000 OPE tasks, each associated to all the candidate estimators in 𝒱𝒱\mathcal{V}caligraphic_V that are 21212121, for a total of 5.25.25.25.2 million samples. Note that we removed the few trivial OPE tasks which had all rewards equal to 0 or 1.

OPE Estimators

The set 𝒱𝒱\mathcal{V}caligraphic_V of candidate estimators includes several model-free, model-based and hybrid estimators, as done in [40]. Estimators hyperparameters, when present, were selected using the SLOPE method [36]. All the estimators used are listed in Table 3, and a brief explanation of each of them is reported in appendix B.

Each of the six estimators with a reward model is employed in conjunction with three reward predictors: Random Forest Classifier and Logistic Regression from the Scikit-Learn444Scikit-Learn available with 3-Clause BSD license: https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn library [28], and LGBM Classifier from the Python package of LightGBM555LightGBM available with MIT license: https://github.com/microsoft/LightGBM/tree/master [16]. The reward models were fitted using a 3-fold cross-fitting procedure to reduce possible overfitting [27].

Features

We compute 43 features for each OPE task that can be categorized into three groups:

  • •

    Policies-independent features, that describe structural properties of the CB scenario and are unrelated from the specific πb,πesubscript𝜋𝑏subscript𝜋𝑒\pi_{b},\ \pi_{e}italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, e.g., the number of rounds, the reward mean and variance, the number of actions.

  • •

    Policies-dependent features, such as the dissimilarity between the two policies πb,πesubscript𝜋𝑏subscript𝜋𝑒\pi_{b},\ \pi_{e}italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_b end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, measured with different geometrical and statistical distances.

  • •

    OPE estimator features, that refer to specific properties of the OPE estimator used in that task, e.g., if the estimator is self-normalized, uses importance sampling, employs a reward model, and if so, which one.

The comprehensive list of features, together with their mathematical formulations, is reported in Appendix E.

Realizations

In order to improve the robustness of the data, both the features and MSE are computed as the average of ng⁢e⁢nsubscript𝑛𝑔𝑒𝑛n_{gen}italic_n start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_g italic_e italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT realizations 𝒯o⁢p⁢e(j)⁢(s)superscriptsubscript𝒯𝑜𝑝𝑒𝑗𝑠\mathcal{T}_{ope}^{(j)}(s)caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_p italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_s ) of each 𝒯o⁢p⁢e(j)superscriptsubscript𝒯𝑜𝑝𝑒𝑗\mathcal{T}_{ope}^{(j)}caligraphic_T start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_o italic_p italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_j ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT. The features and the target MSE are computed for each candidate estimator and averaged across all realizations to obtain the final values used in the meta-learning dataset.

Appendix D Supervised Model Training

Supervised Model

As a supervised model, we select the Random Forest regressor provided by the scikit-learn package777https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.html.

Data Split

In order to train and evaluate the AutoOPE supervised model, we split the meta-learning dataset in 80% for optimization and training, and 20% for testing, so that the testing data never contains OPE tasks the supervised model was trained on.

Hyperparameter Optimization

AutoOPE uses a Random Forest as a supervised model. In order to select the best hyperparameters we rely on a Bayesian Search optimizing the 5-fold cross-validation Regret between the predicted MSE of the OPE estimator selected by AutoOPE, V^m^subscript^𝑉^𝑚\hat{V}_{\hat{m}}over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT over^ start_ARG italic_m end_ARG end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, and the best estimator according to the MSE on the ground-truth dataset. We define the Regret as:

Regret≔M⁢S⁢E⁢(V^m^⁢(πe))−M⁢S⁢E⁢(V^m∗⁢(πe)),≔Regret𝑀𝑆𝐸subscript^𝑉^𝑚subscript𝜋𝑒𝑀𝑆𝐸subscript^𝑉superscript𝑚subscript𝜋𝑒\displaystyle\text{Regret}\coloneqq MSE(\hat{V}_{\hat{m}}(\pi_{e}))-MSE(\hat{V% }_{m^{*}}(\pi_{e}))\ ,Regret ≔ italic_M italic_S italic_E ( over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT over^ start_ARG italic_m end_ARG end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ) - italic_M italic_S italic_E ( over^ start_ARG italic_V end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_π start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ) , (4)

This means that at each step of the Bayesian Search, the training dataset is split into five folds, and a Random Forest regression model (with fixed hyperparameters) is fitted for each of the possible five subsets of four data folds, resulting in five models in total. Each model is then evaluated on the remaining out-of-bag fold in terms of Regret.

The Regret values are averaged over the different five models, and the 5-fold cross-validation metric is obtained, that is the function optimized by the Bayesian Search.

The Bayesian Search is implemented on top of the Scikit-Optimize888Scikit-Optimize available with 3-Clause BSD license: https://github.com/scikit-optimize/scikit-optimize/tree/master library, and involves Bayesian optimization using Gaussian Processes to approximate the objective function, making the assumption that function points are distributed as a multivariate Gaussian. The Bayesian Optimization is executed on the training data, with 100 calls made to optimize the hyperparameters.

Appendix F Additional Experiments and Ablation Studies

F.1 Scaling Experiment

We performed a scaling experiment of AutoOPE by varying the size of the meta-learning dataset ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M. We take 20% of the OPE tasks in ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M as the test set. To investigate the scaling behavior, we train and optimize AutoOPE on different sub-samples of the remaining 80% of the OPE tasks in ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M. The results are reported in Figure 5 and show that the loss (i.e., the Regret) of AutoOPE follows a scaling behavior, which is particularly popular in the recent Deep Learning literature [15, 11]. By increasing the training data, we observe a decrease in the Regret approximately following a power law in the form: L=A+BDα𝐿𝐴𝐵superscript𝐷𝛼L=A+\frac{B}{D^{\alpha}}italic_L = italic_A + divide start_ARG italic_B end_ARG start_ARG italic_D start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_α end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_ARG, where L𝐿Litalic_L is the loss measured with the Regret, D𝐷Ditalic_D is the meta-learning dataset size, and A𝐴Aitalic_A, B𝐵Bitalic_B, and α𝛼\alphaitalic_α are scalar coefficients. While we selected the largest meta-learning dataset for the experimental analysis of this paper, the results in Figure 5 show that the dataset size can be adjusted based on the trade-off between computational resources and model performance for the scenario of interest.

F.2 Additional Ablation Studies

Features

To understand the impact of including different feature numbers and types on AutoOPE’s performance, we conducted the following ablation study. We group the features in the 3 sets defined in the manuscript:

  • •

    policies-dependent;

  • •

    policies-independent;

  • •

    estimators-dependent.

We train 3 models (one for each group) in the same way outlined in Appendix D, and we test them on the same unseen test set used for the scaling experiment. We show the results in Table 5.

From these results, we can see the impact of each feature group: using only estimator-dependent features gives poor results, policies-dependent features are the best individual group of features, and using all the features combined is beneficial. This applies to both regret and Spearman.

Dataset diversity

In order to understand the impact of the meta-dataset characteristics on the performance of AutoOPE, we performed the following ablation study. Here, we simulate different generation methods by subsampling the complete dataset ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M. For this study, we perform two experiments:

  • •

    First, we keep only the OPE tasks with 5 actions or less and train only on these. This experiment should highlight the importance of having tasks with a higher number of actions in the meta-dataset. To compare this generation method with the one used in the paper, we train a model on a random subset of ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M with the same size. The results obtained are reported in Table 6.

  • •

    In the second experiment, we only keep the tasks with a KL-divergence between the policies ≤0.1absent0.1\leq 0.1≤ 0.1. This experiment should highlight the importance of having tasks where the policies are different in the meta-dataset. To compare this generation method with the one used in the paper, we train a model on a random subset of ℳℳ\mathcal{M}caligraphic_M with the same size. The results obtained are reported in Table 7.

From these findings, we can see how a more diverse generation method is beneficial and improves performance compared to a generation method that generates tasks with a low number of actions or with similar logging and evaluation policies.

Results

In order to be able to compute the variance, we perform 20 bootstrap samples of the logging data and we perform the experimental tests on each of them.

The results are shown in Figure 6. AutoOPE consistently outperforms PAS-IF, demonstrating lower Relative Regret and better Spearman’s Rank Correlation Coefficient. Notably, AutoOPE exhibits a much lower variance in particular for the Relative Regret, while PAS-IF exhibits very high variance. These results are consistent with the experiments showed in Section 4 and confirm that AutoOPE is able to generalize to unseen OPE tasks with a different distribution compared to the one used for its training, in a zero-shot scenario.

Results

The results obtained from Logging 1 are reported in Figure 8 while those of Logging 2 in Figure 8. Since these synthetic experiments are the same of [40], we use their optimal values for the other hyperparameters such as the network structure, regularization, learning rate. In both cases our proposed AutoOPE outperforms PAS-IF across almost all evaluation policies in terms of Spearman’s rank correlation coefficient. In terms of Relative Regret, AutoOPE performs similar to PAS-IF in the first half settings of the Logging 1 experiments. However, for high values of βesubscript𝛽𝑒\beta_{e}italic_β start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, PAS-IF slightly outperform AutoOPE. In the Logging 2 set of experiments, we see that for all the βe≥0subscript𝛽𝑒0\beta_{e}\geq 0italic_β start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ≥ 0 AutoOPE outperforms PAS-IF, but PAS-IF performs better in the settings with βe<0subscript𝛽𝑒0\beta_{e}<0italic_β start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_e end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < 0. The fact that AutoOPE exhibits better Spearman’s Rank Correlation indicates that, while both methods predict similar values for the best estimator, AutoOPE is more consistent in ranking all of them.

Appendix G Infrastructure and Computational Time Comparison

For the experiments conducted in this paper, we employed different instances from AWS EC2, to match different needs of resources (GPUs, CPUs) according to the different experiments. The Operating System Ubuntu 20.04 was selected for all the tests.

We used the c6i.32xlarge instance with 128 cores and 256 GB RAM for the synthetic dataset generation explained in Appendix C.2. This instance allows to terminate the whole generation process in about 35 hours.

For the AutoOPE model optimization, training and evaluation instead, additional RAM is needed, since some optimization iterations dive into the training of many and very deep decision trees. The instance used in this case is the m6i.32xlarge instance, with 128 cores and 512 GB RAM. The whole process last approximately 20 hours.

Instead, the experiments described in Section 4 require some hardware accelerator to speed-up the training of the neural network used by PAS-IF. Since the training is very demanding, we adopted the powerful g6.12xlarge instance, that owns four GPUs with 24GB of dedicated memory each, 48 CPUs and 192GB of RAM. Additionally, the PAS-IF code has undergone modifications to enable parallel computation wherever feasible, thereby reducing computational overhead during experimentation. In these experiments, it is apparent the high computational cost of PAS-IF, as shown in Figure 9.

We conduct an additional experiment to test the two Estimator Selection methods on one single synthetic OPE task, so that the maximum level of parallelization could be reached during the execution of PAS-IF. Another factor that affects the time performance is the logging data size, so we perform this experiment different times, varying the logging dataset size. Concerning AutoOPE instead, the model loading time is not negligible, so we test the method under two conditions: in the first condition the black-box model is already present in cache, while in the second the model need to be loaded from disk. The results are reported in Figure 10 and show that even considering the parallelized PAS-IF version and the model loading time for AutoOPE, the time required by PAS-IF to perform the Estimator Selection task exceeds the time needed for AutoOPE to load the model from disk and to perform the same Estimator Selection task. This difference is even higher for larger data sizes.

Appendix I Broader impact statement

With an improved performance in Estimator Selection, we improve the quality of OPE. This may be beneficial to society, allowing decision-makers to test policies that could be potentially dangerous without deploying them on a real system with improved reliability. Furthermore, using a pre-trained and not computationally expensive model can be beneficial in terms of environmental impacts.
